Aim
To write a C++ program that demonstrates the use of class templates, allowing a class to work with different data types.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Declare a class template using template <class T>.
Define data members and member functions inside the template class.
Create objects of the template class with different data types (int, float, etc.).
Call the member functions and display the output.
End the program.

Program (C++ â€“ Class Template Example)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
template <class T>
class Calculator {
    T num1, num2;

public:
    Calculator(T a, T b) {
        num1 = a;
        num2 = b;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Numbers: " << num1 << " & " << num2 << endl;
        cout << "Addition = " << num1 + num2 << endl;
        cout << "Multiplication = " << num1 * num2 << endl;
        cout << "--------------------------" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    cout << "Using Class Template:" << endl;

    Calculator<int> c1(10, 20);          // integer type
    Calculator<float> c2(2.5f, 3.5f);    // float type

    c1.display();
    c2.display();

    return 0;
}

Sample Output (Result)
Using Class Template:
Numbers: 10 & 20
Addition = 30
Multiplication = 200
--------------------------
Numbers: 2.5 & 3.5
Addition = 6
Multiplication = 8.75
--------------------------
Result
The program successfully demonstrates the use of class templates, allowing the same class to operate on different data types such as int and float.
